===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable|rhetoric|literature}} [[deliberate|Deliberate]] or [[unintentional]] [[overstatement]], ''[[particularly]]'' [[extreme]] [[overstatement]].
#* {{RQ:Langley Rhetoric|12|'''''Hyperbole''''' soars too high, or creeps too low,<br/>Exceeds the truth, things wonderful to shew.}}
#* '''1837''', [[w:Nathaniel Hawthorne|Nathaniel Hawthorne]], ''[[s:Legends of the Province House|Legends of the Province House]]''
#*: The great staircase, however, may be termed, without much '''hyperbole''', a feature of grandeur and magnificence.
#* {{RQ:Cooper Deerslayer|III|VIII|248|"Nay, nay, good Sumach," interrupted the Deerslayer, whose love of truth was too indomitable to listen to such '''hyperbole''', with patience{{...}}}}
#* ''c.'' '''1910''', [[w:Theodore Roosevelt|Theodore Roosevelt]], ''[[s:Productive Scholarship|Productive Scholarship]]''
#*: Of course the hymn has come to us from somewhere else, but I do not know from where; and the average native of our village firmly believes that it is indigenous to our own soil—which it can not be, unless it deals in '''hyperbole''', for the nearest approach to a river in our neighborhood is the village pond.
#* '''1987''', {{w|Donald Trump}}, [[w:Tony Schwartz (author)|Tony Schwartz]], ''[[wikiquote:Donald Trump#Trump: The Art of the Deal (1987)|The Art of the Deal]]'', p. 58.
#*: The final key to the way I promote is bravado. I play to people's fantasies. ..People want to believe that something is the biggest and the greatest and the most spectacular. I call it truthful '''hyperbole'''. It's an innocent form of exaggeration—and a very effective form of promotion.
#* {{quote-book|en|author= Richard Klein |chapter= Introduction |title= Cigarettes are sublime |edition= Paperback |location= Durham |publisher= Duke University Press |year= 1995 |year_published= 1993 |isbn= 0-8223-1641-2 |oclc= 613939086 |page= 17 |pageurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=E0i4xgH4vOgC&pg=PA17&lpg=PA17&dq=hyperbole |passage=In these circumstances, '''hyperbole''' is called for, the rhetorical figure that raises its objects up, excessively, way above their actual merit : it is not to deceive by exaggeration that one overshoots the mark, but to allow the true value, the truth of what is insufficiently valued, to appear.}}
#* '''2001''', Tom Bentley, Daniel Stedman Jones, ''The Moral Universe''
#*: The perennial problem, especially for the BBC, has been to reconcile the '''hyperbole'''-driven agenda of newspapers with the requirement of balance, which is crucial to the public service remit.
# {{lb|en|countable}} An [[instance]] or [[example]] of [[such]] [[overstatement]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Troilus and Cressida|act=I|scene=iii|page=601|column=2|text={{...}}and when he ſpeakes, / 'Tis like a Chime a mending. With tearmes vnſquar' / Which from the tongue of roaring ''Typhon'' dropt, / Would ſeemes '''Hyperboles'''}}
#* '''1843''', [[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]], ''[[s:The Gates of Somnauth|The Gates of Somnauth]]''
#*: The honourable gentleman forces us to hear a good deal of this detestable rhetoric; and then he asks why, if the secretaries of the Nizam and the King of Oude use all these tropes and '''hyperboles''', Lord Ellenborough should not indulge in the same sort of eloquence?
# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete}} A [[hyperbola]].

